This paper is likely to belong to the arXiv CS sub-category of Computational Linguistics (cs.CL) because it focuses on improving the performance of distant supervision relation extraction, which is a task in natural language processing. Additionally, the paper proposes a novel approach that uses reinforcement learning and bag-level prediction, which are common techniques in computational linguistics. 

The paper may also belong to the sub-category of Machine Learning (cs.LG) because it uses positive and unlabeled learning, which is a type of semi-supervised learning, to improve the performance of relation extraction. 

Furthermore, the paper may be relevant to the sub-category of Artificial Intelligence (cs.AI) because it proposes a new approach that combines multiple representations to make bag-level prediction, which is a common technique in AI. 

The paper may also be relevant to the sub-category of Information Retrieval (cs.IR) because relation extraction is a task that is often used in information retrieval systems to extract structured information from unstructured text. 

Finally, the paper may be relevant to the sub-category of Neural and Evolutionary Computing (cs.NE) because it uses neural networks to perform relation extraction and improve the performance of the proposed approach.
